<subSubSection id="EFE12826838BCABCD41DD657DB2E0024" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" type="holotype">
<paragraph id="CD5835051A09D63AADEAAC46324ADD46" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F5B6CBC570C1048F84BC581DC02A84C7" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
NORWAY. 
<normalizedToken id="D1C91FC93D4E7D33B1A828D048087EB9" originalValue="Sør-Trøndelag">Sor-Trondelag</normalizedToken>
: Oppdal municipality, Drivdalen, by the rapids in the lower part of the river Kaldvella, 
<geoCoordinate id="6B7F07A258B8B7EF4361EAC53FE0479C" degrees="62" direction="north" minutes="17" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="62.283333">62°17'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="563E20E35AE48AF20B9000D256F8FC14" degrees="9" direction="east" minutes="35" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="9.583333">9°35'E</geoCoordinate>
, alt. 940-980 m, exposed rock face in the subalpine region. 23 July 1993, E. Timdal 7535 (O L-125!), TLC: rangiformic acid, norrangiformic acid, unknown substances.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="35AA1A571F21E21CDE720C84EA83661E" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D2E73C107C5DB000A7B4EC7A1FA9DB87" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="71962832B63D89A8F86852E02D9D68AF" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="89C8EE500B5F4C75371BEC937953FD8C" bold="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">New to Sweden.</emphasis>
The species was previously known only from Norway and Greenland (
<bibRefCitation id="7BD4023AC6075707E9CC96BEBF5EA35C" author="Haugan, R" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="17 - 26" refId="B28" refString="Haugan, R, Timdal, E, 1994. Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea -complex. Graphis Scripta 6: 17 - 26" title="Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea - complex." volume="6" year="1994">Haugan and Timdal 1994</bibRefCitation>
). It resembles the more common 
<taxonomicName id="C6D1563CD92C6FC816EEC18FE1B4F974" genus="C." lsidName="C. aglaea" pageId="4" pageNumber="37" rank="species" species="aglaea">
<emphasis id="7DD6AF2051E81B6E9F69B225C1E47C0E" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">C. aglaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Sommerf.) Hafellner, but differs in forming white areolae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F27C3135C993E5E6E8DB862855518683" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Calvitimela perlata (O L- 195661). Scale: 5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64929" pageId="4" pageNumber="37">4</figureCitation>
), slightly longer ascospores 
<pageBreakToken id="441ABD7684AEA29BA1585F8F65D2A758" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" start="start">(</pageBreakToken>
11.5-17 
<normalizedToken id="C9038EB20DB2E36400C4FFA31F476F27" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7.5 
<normalizedToken id="5585076BE3C68B240BFF048527CAD89C" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FE63FADEE2E73F249CDCAEBA8D8BE2BC" author="Haugan, R" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="17 - 26" refId="B28" refString="Haugan, R, Timdal, E, 1994. Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea -complex. Graphis Scripta 6: 17 - 26" title="Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea - complex." volume="6" year="1994">Haugan and Timdal 1994</bibRefCitation>
), and in the presence of rangiformic and norrangiformic acids in the thallus. In 
<taxonomicName id="3A93E307C1E9EDEEA48CD25D750A2AC8" genus="C." lsidName="C. aglaea" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" rank="species" species="aglaea">
<emphasis id="26F356D6BADDA08959900A9AE2BE1225" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">C. aglaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the areolae are usually pale yellow, the ascospores shorter (9-13.5 
<normalizedToken id="515D586AD7816797C3D3FB097072B9F7" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7.5 
<normalizedToken id="F79F5727EF8260D0D69BF6BCE2721433" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
), and the thallus contains atranorin, bourgeanic acid, usnic acid (rarely lacking), and sometimes stictic acid (
<bibRefCitation id="3EC70791D32EEBC138EC966013088E5F" author="Haugan, R" journalOrPublisher="Graphis Scripta" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="17 - 26" refId="B28" refString="Haugan, R, Timdal, E, 1994. Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea -complex. Graphis Scripta 6: 17 - 26" title="Tephromela perlata and T. talayana, with notes on the T. aglaea - complex." volume="6" year="1994">Haugan and Timdal 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="A6CC09B15919C80DF08B33B7DAD0EC95" ID-Zenodo-Dep="973734" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.11.6670.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/64929" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph id="9CF6A5C7B5166C06A08246FC8510BD70" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis id="632B8189E13D3FDDA254DBFC3867A2E2" bold="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Figure 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="B6488AEFCDEBB0850A183D0AD5673939" authorityName="R. Sant" authorityYear="2004" baseAuthorityName="Haugan &amp; Timdal" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Mycoblastaceae" genus="Calvitimela" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Calvitimela perlata" order="Lecanorales" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="perlata">
<emphasis id="949EFA160017B5FB014F2BD085243AAE" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Calvitimela perlata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(O L-195661). Scale: 5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="2576F2728488F7D916B1AE3D22A6885B" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">In Norway, the species grows on sun-exposed, more or less sloping rock surfaces, often where water is trickling or near rivers or waterfalls in the subalpine and alpine regions. The Swedish locality is a boulder in the alpine region.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D2AEF10CA5E0D67570D095C0FE3D0588" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" type="specimen examined">
<paragraph id="921930BB37D323CA8E95A161D09439E8" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Specimen examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="825C5C802EF0A1EE12CF52B726799F5F" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
SWEDEN. Torne Lappmark: 
<normalizedToken id="509A12C668C51DF35992CC7810B29B55" originalValue="Låktatjåkka">Laktatjakka</normalizedToken>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="84139E88FD5EE67198D27A98226A964C" degrees="68" direction="north" minutes="24.87" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="68.4145">68°24.87'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="32C0E53471684ACC7A2D9CD103280F3E" degrees="18" direction="east" minutes="19.07" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="18.317833">18°19.07'E</geoCoordinate>
, alt. 640 m, steep face of boulder in the low alpine region. 8 July 2014, Timdal 13464-1 (O L-195661), TLC: rangiformic acid (major). norrangiformic acid (minor), unknown substances (minor).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
